{{Infobox NRHP | name =Canton House | nrhp_type = | image = Canton House, 300 Water St., Baltimore City, Maryland.JPG | caption = Canton House in 2011 | location= 300 Water Street, at South Street, [[Baltimore, Maryland]] | coordinates = {{coord|39|17|20|N|76|36|39|W|display=inline,title}} | locmapin = United States Baltimore#Maryland#USA | built = {{Start date|1923}} | architecture = Colonial Revival | added = December 13, 1978 | area = less than one acre | governing_body = Private | refnum = 78003140<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref> }} '''Canton House''' is a historic [[office building]] located on the northeast corner of Water Street and South Street in [[Baltimore]], [[Maryland]], [[United States]]. It is a {{frac|4|1|2}}-story [[Colonial Revival]]-style building, with seven bays across the front façade of Water Street to the south and three bays across the side facing South Street to the west. The first story level is in [[marble]] and brick is laid in [[Flemish bond]] from the second story up. It has a sloped peaked roof with two dormer windows facing west to the side. The main entrance features two fluted [[Corinthian order|Corinthian]] stone columns.
It was constructed in 1923 as the headquarters of one of Baltimore's oldest, largest and most colorful businesses, [[Canton Iron Works|The Canton Company]], a business established in 1828 by [[Peter Cooper]] (1791-1883), noted engineer and industrialist most remembered for inventing and manufacturing the ''[[Tom Thumb (locomotive)|Tom Thumb]]'' [[steam locomotive]] for the recently established [[Baltimore and Ohio Railroad]], the first passenger railway line in America in 1827 as it made its transition from using horse power to [[steam engine|steam power]] to pull its railroad cars on the first segment of the line from Baltimore southwest to [[Ellicott City, Maryland|Ellicott Mills, Maryland]] on the upper [[Patapsco River]] from [[Baltimore Harbor|Helen Delich Bentley Port of Baltimore]]. [[Columbus O'Donnell]], the son of [[John O'Donnell (sea captain)|John O'Donnell]], a sea captain who brought in the first trade cargos from [[Guangzhou|Canton, China]] to Baltimore and America in 1784, along with [[William Patterson (Maryland)|William Patterson]] (1752-1835), a noted city merchant, civic leader, co-founder of the [[Baltimore and Ohio Railroad]] and the father of the infamous [[Elizabeth Patterson Bonaparte|Elizabeth ("Betsy") Patterson Bonaparte]], the "Belle of Baltimore", who married [[Jerome Bonaparte]] on Christmas Eve, December 24, 1803, the younger brother of the [[First French Empire|French]] Emperor [[Napoleon Bonaparte|Napoleon I]] and the donater of land for nearby [[Patterson Park]] in 1827.
The Company was established to develop the industrial, commercial and residential potential of the large tract of land along the north shore of the Patapsco's Northwest Branch, east of the [[Inner Harbor|Inner Harbor (then called "The Basin")]] and southeast of old [[History of Baltimore|Baltimore Town]] and neighboring [[Fells Point, Baltimore]] <ref name="mht_ihp">{{cite web|url=https://mht.maryland.gov/secure/medusa/PDF/NR_PDFs/NR-513.pdf |title=National Register of Historic Places Registration: Canton House|date=1977|accessdate=2016-03-01 |author=Bill Tamburrino|publisher=Maryland Historical Trust}}</ref>
The Canton House was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 1978.<ref name="nris"/>
