===Football in Australia===

A long time supporter of [[soccer in Australia|Association football]] in Australia, Lowy was Chairman of the [[Football Federation Australia]] (FFA) from 2003 to November 2015.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.smh.com.au/sport/soccer/end-of-an-era-brings-legacy-of-ffa-chairman-frank-lowy-into-focus-20151105-gkra8u.html |title=End of an era |author=Sygall, David |date=7 November 2015}}</ref> Some observers credit him and [[John O'Neill (sport administrator)|John O'Neill]], a former [[rugby union]] executive, with resurrecting soccer in Australia.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-11-16/frank-lowy-not-a-perfect-score,-but-positives/6945354|title=Frank Lowy transformed soccer in Australia|author=Galloway, Patrick|work=ABC.net |date=16 November 2015 |accessdate=16 February 2016}}</ref>  A televised  "[[A-League]]" is now in place, and the country has become a member of the [[Asian Football Confederation]].

In 2007 Lowy commenced a campaign to host the [[2022 FIFA World Cup]] in Australia backed with $43 million in support from the Australian Government.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2015-11-17/lowy-insists-australia-ran-clean-world-cup-bid/6945680 | title=Frank Lowy: Australia ran clean World Cup bid, outgoing billionaire FFA boss says |author=Sales, Leigh |date=18 November 2015}}</ref> In 2010, amid allegations of bribery, politics, and back-scratching,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/sport/the-moment-lowy-knew-cup-bid-was-lost/story-fn76vhk4-1225965439906 |title=The moment Lowy knew Cup bid was lost |author=Wilson, Peter |work=The Australian |date=4 December 2010 |accessdate=30 July 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1185986/index.htm |work=Sports Illustrated |publisher=Time Inc |location=United States |title=Sorry Soccer: New allegations of corruption underline the need for change in FIFA |author=Wahl, Grant |date=23 May 2011 |accessdate=30 July 2011 |page=16 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/13590264.stm |title=Bin Hammam denied access to Fifa congress |work=BBC News |location=United Kingdom |date=1 June 2011 |accessdate=30 July 2011 }}</ref> FIFA awarded Qatar the rights to host the World Cup.

In 2015, he fell off a stage as the A-League trophy was due to be presented. In May 2015 he underwent surgery to resolve a complication that had arisen from the fall.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/frank-lowy-falls-off-stage-a-league-trophy-presentation-for-melbourne-victory-overshadowed-as-84-10256081.html |title=Frank Lowy falls off stage: A-League trophy presentation for Melbourne Victory overshadowed by 84-year-old falling from stage |work=The Independent |author=Rice, Simon |date=17 May 2015 |accessdate=23 June 2017 }}</ref>

[[File:Frank Lowy presented with Woodrow Wilson Award (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|Lowy receiving the [[Woodrow Wilson Awards|Woodrow Wilson Award for Corporate Citizenship]] in 2005]]

===Philanthropy===
Lowy has a reputation for giving of his time and financial support to a broad range of causes.{{citation needed|date=January 2014}}

Awarded the title of Australia’s leading philanthropist by peak body, Philanthropy Australia, with donations in 2002 of A$10 million,.<ref name="crikey">{{cite news |url=http://www.crikey.com.au/2006/05/17/forget-the-filthy-rich-heres-the-crikey-philanthropy-list/ |title=Forget the filthy rich: here’s the Crikey philanthropy list |author1=Nethercote, Jane |author2=Webb-Pullman, Marika |work=Crikey.com |location=Australian |date=17 May 2006 |accessdate=29 July 2011 }}</ref>

In April 2003 to mark the 50th anniversary of his arrival in Australia, Lowy established the [[Lowy Institute for International Policy]], an independent international policy [[think tank]] devoted to foreign affairs, and Australia's role in the world.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.lowyinstitute.org/AboutUs.asp |title=About the Lowy Institute |publisher=The Lowy Institute |accessdate=4 December 2006 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061224184847/http://lowyinstitute.org/AboutUs.asp |archivedate=24 December 2006 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> It was reported that a gift of A$30 million was made to establish the Institute.<ref name="crikey"/> Together with the [[Kerry Packer|Packer]] family, in 2008 Lowy donated an undisclosed amount towards the [[Victor Chang]] [[Victor Chang Cardiac Research Institute|Cardiac Research Institute]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Tovey, Josephine |date=3 September 2008 |url=http://www.smh.com.au/articles/2008/09/03/1220121292786.html |title=Princess Mary opens Victor Chang centre |work=The Sydney Morning Herald |accessdate=29 July 2011}}</ref> In 2010, Lowy and his family donated A$10 million to facilitate the construction of the [[UNSW Lowy Cancer Research Centre]], a collaborative centre of the Children’s Cancer Institute Australia and the Faculty of Medicine at the [[University of New South Wales]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://keyprojects.unsw.edu.au/project/lowy-cancer-research-centre |title=Lowy Cancer Research Centre |work=Key projects |publisher=University of New South Wales |accessdate=29 July 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110709162106/http://keyprojects.unsw.edu.au/project/lowy-cancer-research-centre |archivedate=9 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.med.unsw.edu.au/medweb.nsf/page/LowyGiving+Hope |title=The Lowy Cancer Research Centre at UNSW – Giving Hope |date=1 August 2010 |work=Alumni e-Newsletter |publisher=University of New South Wales |accessdate=29 July 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110407170055/http://www.med.unsw.edu.au/medweb.nsf/page/LowyGiving+Hope |archivedate=7 April 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=About the Lowy Gift|url=http://www.lowycancerresearchcentre.unsw.edu.au/about-us/about-lowy-gift|work=The Centre is named in recognition of leading businessman and philanthropist Frank Lowy and his family|publisher=UNSW Medicine|accessdate=23 January 2014}}</ref>
{{Clear}}

==Awards and recognition==
In 2000, he was appointed a [[Companion of the Order of Australia]] for his service to the community through the development of the property industry and expansion of the retail sector in Australia and internationally, and as philanthropist committed to support of wide-ranging social and cultural endeavours.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itsanhonour.gov.au/honours/honour_roll/search.cfm?aus_award_id=1129636&search_type=quick&showInd=true |title=Search Australian Honours: Lowy, Frank P |date=26 January 2000 |accessdate=29 July 2011 |work=It's an Honour |publisher=Commonwealth of Australia }}</ref> The establishment of the Lowy Institute led him to being awarded the [[Woodrow Wilson Awards|Woodrow Wilson Award for Corporate Citizenship]] in 2005 by the [[Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/National/Howard-gets-award-amid-antiUS-concern/2005/08/21/1124562729594.html|agency=[[Australian Associated Press|AAP]]|work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]]|accessdate=6 January 2008|date=21 August 2005|title=Howard gets award amid anti-US concern}}</ref> On 2 October 2007 Lowy received the Henni Friedlander Award for the Common Good at [[Bowdoin College]] in [[Brunswick, Maine]], [[United States]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bowdoin.edu/news/events/archives/004471.shtml|publisher=[[Bowdoin College]]|accessdate=2 October 2007|date=2 October 2007|title=Business Leader/Philanthropist Frank Lowy to Receive Henni Friedlander Award for the Common Good}}</ref> In 2008 Lowy was honoured by [[Australia Post]] for his contribution to philanthropy as one of the nation's five leading, living philanthropists with a [[commemorative stamp|commemorative]] [[postage stamp]] that was released on the eve of Australia Day as part of the [[Australian Legends]] series.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.theage.com.au/national/new-stamps-honour-five-philanthropists-20080125-1o6n.html |title=New stamps honour five philanthropists |work=The Age |date=25 January 2008 |accessdate=30 July 2011 |agency=AAP }}</ref>

He was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in the [[2017 Birthday Honours#United Kingdom|2017 Queen's Birthday Honours]] (UK) for services to business and philanthropy.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=61962|supp=y|page=B2|date=17 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.afr.com/real-estate/commercial/once-an-illegal-immigrant-now-a-knight-bachelor-arise-sir-frank-lowy-20170615-gwrlaw |title=Once an illegal immigrant, now a Knight Bachelor, arise Sir Frank Lowy |author=Margo, Jill |work=Australian Financial Review |date=15 June 2017 |accessdate=17 June 2017 }}</ref>

