{{Infobox State Senator | name = George D. Buffett | image= | image_size=160px | caption = | office=Member of the [[New Mexico House of Representatives]] for the 24th district | term=1979–2002 | predecessor = | successor = | constituency = | state2 = | state_senate2 = | district2 = | term2= | majority = | party = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] | birth_date = {{Birth date|1928|11|19}} | birth_place =[[Casper, Wyoming]], United States | death_date={{death date and age|2012|10|13|1928|11|19}} | death_place =[[Albuquerque, New Mexico]], United States | profession =businessman | residence =[[Albuquerque, New Mexico]] | relations=[[Warren Buffett]] | alma_mater=[[University of New Mexico]] | spouse = Jeanette Franzen | religion = presbyterian | children= | website = |branch= |serviceyears= |rank= |battles= |allegiance= }} '''George Duval Buffett''' (November 19, 1928 &ndash; October 13, 2012) was an American politician who was a Republican member of the [[New Mexico House of Representatives]] from 1979 to 2002.<ref>[http://www.nmlegis.gov/lcs/legislator_details_archive.aspx?SponsorCode=HBUFF New Mexico Legislature Senator George Buffett]</ref> Buffett attended [[University of New Mexico]] and was a businessman.<ref>[http://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/8356/george-duval-buffett#.VEZsrYt4pk8 Votesmart-George Buffett]</ref> He died in 2012.<ref>[http://www.koat.com/news/new-mexico/albuquerque/Legendary-Buffett-s-founder-politician-dies/17002078 Legendary Buffett's founder and politician dies]</ref> He was an arch-conservative state representative, owner of Buffett's Candy and cousin of [[Warren Buffett]].
George's interest in politics stemmed from his uncle, congressman [[Howard Homan Buffett]]. He attended the [[Republican National Convention 1952]] in Chicago. He served as a State Representative for 24 years (1979-2002). He was a fiscal conservative. He started writing a political newsletter, called Buffett's Bullets, to educate and to provide insight into the inner workings of politics in NM from 1989 through 2008 and had a mailing list that grew from 150 to over 10,000 people from across the state.<ref>[http://www.buffettsbullets.com/ Buffett's Bullets]</ref> He also served as the Republican National Committeeman for the State of NM for four years (2004-2008) and he again attended the [[Republican National Convention 2008]] in Minneapolis.
George founded B&H Company in 1952, which ran concessions at various fiestas and fairs across the state. This business also ran the concessions at the ABQ Zoo for 16 years, the concessions at Speedway Park, the concessions at the Civic Auditorium and the concessions at the ABQ Dukes for 18 years. This business grew into B&H Wholesale, which supplies other concessionaires, their products and currently distributes across the state of NM and into parts of AZ, CO, OK, TX and UT. In 1956, George founded Buffett's Candies.<ref>[http://www.buffettscandies.com/about.php Buffett's Candies]</ref> George founded also the Popcorn Cannery, which produces and distributes pre-popped and flavored popcorn to grocery stores in ABQ. Legislative financial disclosure forms have listed George's ownership of unspecified shares in Warren Buffett's [[Berkshire Hathaway]].
